formulas.formula:
Here's a complete formula sheet for CBSE Class 11 Economics - Comparative Development Experiences of India in JSON format:

```json
[
  {
    "name": "Gross Domestic Product (GDP) Formula",
    "formula": "GDP = C + I + G + (X - M)",
    "variables": {
      "C": "Consumer Expenditure",
      "I": "Investment",
      "G": "Government Expenditure",
      "X": "Exports",
      "M": "Imports"
    },
    "units": "Currency (e.g., $, ₹)",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Gross National Product (GNP) Formula",
    "formula": "GNP = GDP + (Foreign Incomes) - (Foreign Expenditures)",
    "variables": {
      "GDP": "Gross Domestic Product",
      "Foreign Incomes": "Incomes earned by citizens abroad",
      "Foreign Expenditures": "Expenditures made by citizens abroad"
    },
    "units": "Currency (e.g., $, ₹)",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Gross National Income (GNI) Formula",
    "formula": "GNI = GNP - (Depreciation)",
    "variables": {
      "GNP": "Gross National Product",
      "Depreciation": "Value of assets worn out or consumed during the year"
    },
    "units": "Currency (e.g., $, ₹)",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Human Development Index (HDI) Formula",
    "formula": "HDI = 1/3 (Life Expectancy at Birth) + 1/3 (Expected Years of Schooling) + 1/3 (Gross National Income per capita)",
    "variables": {
      "Life Expectancy at Birth": "Average number of years a newborn is expected to live",
      "Expected Years of Schooling": "Average number of years of education a person can expect to receive",
      "Gross National Income per capita": "Total income of the country divided by its population"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Per Capita Income Formula",
    "formula": "Per Capita Income = Total Income / Population",
    "variables": {
      "Total Income": "Total income of the country",
      "Population": "Total number of people in the country"
    },
    "units": "Currency (e.g., $, ₹)",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Poverty Line Formula",
    "formula": "Poverty Line = Minimum amount of income required to meet basic needs",
    "variables": {
      "Minimum amount of income": "Amount of income required to meet basic needs"
    },
    "units": "Currency (e.g., $, ₹)",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Gini Coefficient Formula",
    "formula": "Gini Coefficient = 2 * (∫[0,1] F(x) dx) - 1",
    "variables": {
      "F(x)": "Distribution function of income",
      "dx": "Differential of x"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Kuznets Curve Formula",
    "formula": "Inequality decreases as income increases initially, then increases as income grows further",
    "variables": {
      "Inequality": "Measure of income inequality",
      "Income": "Gross Domestic Product per capita"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Lewis Turning Point Formula",
    "formula": "Turning point occurs when the supply of labor from agriculture equals the demand for labor in industry",
    "variables": {
      "Supply of labor from agriculture": "Number of people leaving agriculture and moving to industry",
      "Demand for labor in industry": "Number of people required by industry"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  },
  {
    "name": "Lewis Model Formula",
    "formula": "Surplus labor in agriculture is absorbed by industry, leading to economic growth",
    "variables": {
      "Surplus labor in agriculture": "Number of people in agriculture who are not fully employed",
      "Industry": "Sector that absorbs surplus labor"
    },
    "units": "",
    "notes": ""
  }
]
```

Please note that this is not an exhaustive list of formulas. The list includes some of the most relevant and commonly used formulas in the chapter on Comparative Development Experiences of India.
